ce:section.ce:para:
To produce ammonia sensing systems, the sensor samples were mounted onto a quartz tube. A valve was used to control the constant flow of reference air into the tube at an adjusted flow rate of 1 L/min. The required ammonia level was prepared from aqueous ammonia (NH3.H2O) which was injected into Duran bottle container. Then the air as carrier gas was flowed through the headspace of a bottle chamber to take the individual gas entering into the gas testing system. The individual gas concentration was controlled by valve to attain the required gas level in gas sensing system. Specific ammonia concentrations were adjusted in a range of 1−1000 ppm to record the gas response data at room temperature (27 °C) at a relative humidity of 65 % RH. The ammonia sensing response under a relative humidity of 90 % RH was also assessed. To control the relative humidity level, the ultrasonic humidifier was used to continuously generate the saturated water stream that was passed into the testing system by inlet valve. The actually relative humidity level is monitored via hygrometer. To measure the ammonia sensing characteristics, a constant DC electrical voltage of 10 V was applied through the sensors and the electrical current was recorded using a Keithley 6485 picoammeter. The sensor resistance was calculated as the ratio of electrical voltage and current and used to investigate the sensor performance. The sensor response was defined as the ratio of the resistance in an air atmosphere (Ra
                        ) to a gas atmosphere (Rg
                        ), which was used to improve the sensor response. Increasingly, the sensor impedance characteristics were investigated by LCR meter with frequencies ranging of 150 Hz −100 kHz under AC input signal. The selectivity of the ammonia sensors to ethanol and acetone was compared.
